xplore the current and future state of spectrum governance worldwide. Spectrum is a foundational component of our contemporary communication infrastructure. The stakes are massive: mobile network operators have invested billions of dollars via national spectrum auctions to claim exclusive use of prime spectrum bands. Despite this windfall for national governments, many people around the globe remain disconnected from mobile service, yet international policy comparisons that can help us understand these disparities and differences are rare. Frequencies offers illuminating case studies from around the world, including Finland, Mexico, New Zealand, India, and Canada, as well as forward-thinking approaches to our use of radio frequencies that encourage greater public benefit and technological advancement. The contributors to Frequencies represent a wide array of disciplinary backgrounds, united by the common goal of maximizing the value and access to the public good that is the radio spectrum. Spectrum policy affects everyone, whether while listening to the radio, making an emergency phone call, or scrolling through social media updates. Frequencies seeks to broaden the discussion about our management of this primary resource necessary for how the world shares information.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBroadband communication systemsxGovernment policy. 0aRadio frequency allocationxGovernment policy. 0aRadio resource management (Wireless communications) 0aTelecommunication policy. 0aTelecommunicationxInternational cooperation. 0aWireless communication systemsxGovernment policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Communication Policy.2bisacsh1 aAla-Fossi, Marko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCave, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/